      },
      "id": 903,
      "panels": [
        {
          "fieldConfig": {
            "defaults": {},
            "overrides": []
          },
          "gridPos": {
            "h": 12,
            "w": 8,
            "x": 0,
            "y": 1
          },
          "id": 904,
          "options": {
            "code": {
              "language": "plaintext",
              "showLineNumbers": false,
              "showMiniMap": false
            },
            "content": "# 📊 Signal Quality Metrics\n\n## RSRP (Reference Signal Received Power)\nMeasures the power of the LTE/5G reference signals.\n\n**Unit:** dBm (decibel-milliwatts)\n\n**Values:**\n- **> -80 dBm** 🟢 Excellent - Strong signal\n- **-80 to -90 dBm** 🟡 Good - Normal signal\n- **-90 to -100 dBm** 🟠 Fair - Weak signal\n- **< -100 dBm** 🔴 Poor - Very weak signal\n\n**What it means:** Higher values (closer to 0) indicate stronger signal reception from the cell tower.\n\n---\n\n## RSSI (Received Signal Strength Indicator)\nMeasures the total received power including signal and interference.\n\n**Unit:** dBm\n\n**Values:**\n- **> -65 dBm** 🟢 Excellent\n- **-65 to -75 dBm** 🟡 Good\n- **-75 to -85 dBm** 🟠 Fair\n- **< -85 dBm** 🔴 Poor\n\n**What it means:** Overall signal strength including noise. Similar to RSRP but includes interference.\n\n---\n\n## SINR (Signal-to-Interference-plus-Noise Ratio)\nMeasures signal quality by comparing signal to noise/interference.\n\n**Unit:** dB (decibels)\n\n**Values:**\n- **> 20 dB** 🟢 Excellent - High data rates possible\n- **13 to 20 dB** 🟡 Good - Reliable connection\n- **0 to 13 dB** 🟠 Fair - Marginal performance\n- **< 0 dB** 🔴 Poor - Connection issues likely\n\n**What it means:** Higher SINR = cleaner signal with less interference. Critical for data speeds.",
            "mode": "markdown"
          },
          "pluginVersion": "12.2.0",
          "title": "",
          "type": "text"
        },
        {
          "fieldConfig": {
            "defaults": {},
            "overrides": []
          },
          "gridPos": {
            "h": 12,
            "w": 8,
            "x": 8,
            "y": 1
          },
          "id": 905,
          "options": {
            "code": {
              "language": "plaintext",
              "showLineNumbers": false,
              "showMiniMap": false
            },
            "content": "## RSRQ (Reference Signal Received Quality)\nMeasures signal quality considering both signal strength and interference.\n\n**Unit:** dB\n\n**Values:**\n- **> -5 dB** 🟢 Excellent\n- **-5 to -10 dB** 🟡 Good\n- **-10 to -15 dB** 🟠 Fair\n- **< -15 dB** 🔴 Poor\n\n**What it means:** Indicates how clean the signal is. Low values suggest high interference or weak signal.\n\n---\n\n# 📡 LTE Bands\n\n## Primary LTE Bands in Use:\n\n- **LTE_BC1 (Band 1)** - 2100 MHz - Long range, good coverage\n- **LTE_BC3 (Band 3)** - 1800 MHz - Balanced coverage/capacity\n- **LTE_BC7 (Band 7)** - 2600 MHz - High capacity, shorter range\n- **LTE_BC20 (Band 20)** - 800 MHz - Excellent penetration, rural areas\n\n**Carrier Aggregation (CA):** Your router combines multiple bands simultaneously for higher speeds.\n\n---\n\n# 🚀 5G NR Bands\n\n## NR5G_N28 (Band n28)\n- **Frequency:** 700 MHz\n- **Type:** Low-band 5G (Sub-6 GHz)\n- **Coverage:** Excellent - Wide area coverage\n- **Speed:** Moderate - Good balance of coverage and speed\n- **Penetration:** Very good - Works well indoors\n\n**NR5G-NSA:** Non-Standalone 5G - Uses LTE as anchor, adds 5G for speed boost.",
            "mode": "markdown"
          },
          "pluginVersion": "12.2.0",
          "title": "",
          "type": "text"
        },
        {
          "fieldConfig": {
            "defaults": {},
            "overrides": []
          },
          "gridPos": {
            "h": 12,
            "w": 8,
            "x": 16,
            "y": 1
          },
          "id": 902,
          "options": {
            "code": {
              "language": "plaintext",
              "showLineNumbers": false,
              "showMiniMap": false
            },
            "content": "# 🔧 Technical Metrics\n\n## CQI (Channel Quality Indicator)\n**Range:** 0-15\n**Meaning:** Indicates channel quality for adaptive modulation\n- **12-15:** Excellent - High-order modulation possible\n- **7-11:** Good - Medium modulation\n- **0-6:** Poor - Low-order modulation only\n\n---\n\n## MCS (Modulation and Coding Scheme)\n**Range:** 0-28 (LTE), 0-31 (5G)\n**Meaning:** Defines data encoding method\n- **Higher values:** More data per transmission (requires good signal)\n- **Lower values:** More robust but slower\n\n---\n\n## Bandwidth\n**Unit:** MHz (Megahertz)\n**Common values:**\n- **5 MHz:** Minimum LTE bandwidth\n- **10 MHz:** Standard allocation\n- **20 MHz:** High capacity\n- **40-100 MHz:** Carrier aggregation total\n\n**UL:** Uplink (upload)\n**DL:** Downlink (download)\n\n---\n\n# 🏢 Network Identifiers\n\n## Cell ID\nUnique identifier for the cell tower/sector you're connected to.\n\n## eNodeB ID\nIdentifies the physical cell tower (Evolved Node B).\n\n## Physical Cell ID\nUsed for radio synchronization (0-503).\n\n## TAC (Tracking Area Code)\nDefines the location area for mobility management.\n\n---\n\n# 📶 Connection Types\n\n**NR5G-NSA:** Non-Standalone 5G using LTE anchor\n**NR5G-SA:** Standalone 5G (pure 5G core)\n**LTE:** 4G LTE only",
            "mode": "markdown"
          },
          "pluginVersion": "12.2.0",
          "title": "",
          "type": "text"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Metrics Guide",
      "type": "row"
    },
