      "id": 50,
      "options": {
        "code": {
          "language": "plaintext",
          "showLineNumbers": false,
          "showMiniMap": false
        },
        "content": "# 📡 Physical Cell ID (PCI) Tracking\n\n## What is Physical Cell ID?\n\nThe **Physical Cell ID (PCI)** is a unique identifier for each cell sector:\n- **LTE**: Values from 0 to 503\n- **5G NR**: Values from 0 to 1007\n\nEach tower sector broadcasts a unique PCI that your device uses to distinguish between different cells.\n\n## Why Track PCI?\n\n### Handover Detection\nWhen the PCI changes, it means your device has **switched to a different cell tower or sector**. This is called a handover or cell reselection.\n\n**Reasons for handovers:**\n- Moving between coverage areas\n- Signal quality degradation\n- Network load balancing\n- Tower maintenance\n\n### Connection Stability\n- **Few changes**: Stable connection, good signal\n- **Frequent changes**: Possible issues:\n  - Weak signal at cell edge\n  - Interference between towers\n  - Network configuration issues\n  - Physical obstacles\n\n## How to Read the Chart\n\nThe **Physical Cell ID History** chart below shows PCI over time:\n\n- **Flat lines**: Connected to same cell (stable)\n- **Steps/jumps**: Handover occurred (cell changed)\n- **Frequent steps**: Unstable connection area\n\nThe legend shows:\n- **Last**: Current PCI\n- **Min/Max**: Range of PCIs used\n- **Delta**: Number of different cells visited\n\n## Tips\n\n✅ **Stable is good**: Fewer handovers = better performance  \n⚠️ **Too many changes**: Consider antenna repositioning  \n📍 **Track locations**: Note where handovers occur frequently",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "pluginVersion": "12.2.0",
      "title": "ℹ️ About Cell ID Tracking",
      "type": "text"
    },
